<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. alboapicalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboapicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">P. alboapicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hering from Burma in the presence of an apical hyaline band extending from cell r2+3 to cell m1 but can be differentiated by the presence of a single hyaline indentation in cell r2+3, versus two hyaline indentations and spot in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. alboapicalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboapicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">P. alboapicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the apical hyaline band restricted to the apical one-third of cell r2+3, versus the whole of apex of cell r2+3 in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. alboapicalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboapicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">P. alboapicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and the hyaline indentations in cell cua ending well before vein CuA, unlike in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. alboapicalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alboapicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">P. alboapicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where they almost reach vein CuA.
</paragraph>
